-- id=71: CSIR 10-Year Foundational Digital Capabilities Research Programme (len=246)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The CSIR''s 10-Year Foundational Digital Capabilities Research Programme seeks Treasury and DSIT funding approval to build shared national infrastructure in artificial intelligence, quantum computing, high-performance computing (HPC), and advanced cybersecurity research. The CSIR hosts SA''s only FLOPS-class supercomputing facility (CHPC, operated jointly with DHET) and the programme proposes tripling national HPC capacity by 2030 through a co-investment model between CSIR, universities, and anchor industry partners. The Parliamentary Portfolio Committee on Science and Technology received briefings in October 2024 flagging that SA invests under 0.8% of GDP in R&D—below the 1.5% OECD baseline—and that without foundational computational infrastructure, AI and data-science ambitions remain dependent on foreign cloud providers. The MTBPS 2025 science budget holds flat in real terms, requiring the programme to demonstrate a blended-finance model (National Research Foundation co-investment, industry partnerships, African Development Bank digital infrastructure facility). The 10-year mandate provides policy continuity across election cycles, with parliamentary oversight benchmarks at years 3, 6, and 10.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s national HPC capacity ranks below that of several African peers; closing this gap is the precondition for competing in the AI-driven global economy. — PC on Science and Technology briefing, October 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Science and Innovation / CSIR / NRF',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. Requires new budget line (est. R800m–R1.2bn over MTEF). Blended-finance model via NRF and industry co-investment reduces fiscal burden. DSIT has policy appetite; Treasury envelope is the binding constraint.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 71;

-- id=85: Merchant Shipping and Maritime Industry Development (len=249)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Merchant Shipping and Maritime Industry Development reform centres on the Merchant Shipping Bill (introduced 2024), which establishes a competitive SA ship registry, strengthens cabotage provisions favouring SA-flagged vessels on coastal routes, and imposes training obligations on operators serving SA ports—creating a pipeline for the domestic maritime workforce. South Africa''s coastline of 2,800 km handles over 90% of export cargo by volume, yet fewer than 1,500 South Africans hold active seafarer certification and SA''s ship registry is commercially negligible. The reform aligns with the DTIC''s Operation Phakisa Ocean Economy roadmap, which identified maritime transport as one of five priority ocean-economy sectors with an estimated R177 billion GDP potential by 2033. The Parliamentary Portfolio Committee on Transport scrutinised the Bill in 2024, with the primary debate centring on the balance between cabotage protectionism (which raises shipping costs) and the development dividend of building local maritime capacity. Fiscal linkage: SAMSA (South African Maritime Safety Authority) requires R150m in additional annual budget to staff the expanded registry and inspection mandate. The reform also connects to the Transnet port concessioning agenda (id=59), as private terminal operators will require more flexible crewing and vessel-flagging rules.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa is a coastal nation whose citizens are almost entirely absent from the maritime profession—this is an anomaly the Merchant Shipping Bill must begin to correct. — PC on Transport, 2024 BRRR',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / SAMSA / DTIC',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. Bill tabled but not yet enacted. Cabotage provisions face opposition from international shipping lines. SAMSA capacity build-up (R150m/year) is fiscally feasible within the existing transport grants framework.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 85;

-- id=94: Inclusive Education: Special Needs Schools and Full-Service Schools Expansion (len=249)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Screening, Identification, Assessment and Support (SIAS) policy (2014) obliges every public school to identify learners with special needs and provide appropriate support, but implementation has stalled: only 456 special schools serve the entire country, 76,000 teaching posts in special schools are unfilled, and the DBE estimates over 600,000 children with moderate to severe disabilities are currently out of school or receiving no meaningful support. This reform proposes a phased expansion of the full-service school network (schools reconfigured to serve learners with mild to moderate learning barriers alongside mainstream learners), from approximately 800 to 2,500 within five years, combined with a targeted training programme to produce qualified remedial teachers and educational psychologists. The Education White Paper 3 on Special Needs provides the policy framework; the Norms and Standards for School Funding must be amended to include a per-capita inclusive education supplement. Parliamentary BRRRs from the PC on Basic Education (2022–2024) consistently flag the absence of a funded roadmap as the critical gap. Fiscal estimate: R4–6 billion in capital (classroom adaptation, assistive technology) plus R3 billion annually in additional staffing.',
  key_quote = 'Over 600,000 South African children with disabilities are not in school—a rights violation and a human capital loss we can no longer afford. — PC on Basic Education BRRR, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Basic Education / DBE / Provincial Education Departments',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate fiscal cost. Legislative framework (SIAS policy, White Paper 3) exists. Bottleneck is teacher training capacity and classroom adaptation capital. NHI-style phased rollout with monitoring is the recommended approach.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 94;

-- id=95: Rural School Consolidation Policy (len=257)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Draft Rural Education Policy on school rationalisation (circulated 2020, not yet gazetted) proposes consolidating non-viable rural schools—defined as those with fewer than 100 learners—into better-resourced hub schools within 30 km, supported by publicly funded scholar transport. Approximately 4,200 South African public schools have fewer than 100 learners; these micro-schools absorb disproportionate per-learner costs (often R40,000–80,000 per learner vs. the national average of R18,000), while offering fewer subject choices, poorer infrastructure, and less experienced teachers due to the remote postings problem. The HEDCOM Ministerial Task Team on Rural Education (2022) found that consolidation with adequate transport can raise learner outcomes by 0.4–0.6 standard deviations in literacy by Grade 6. Implementation requires coordination between DBE, DoT (scholar transport contracts), and provincial MECs, with strong community consultation mechanisms to manage the social and political friction of school closures. The MTBPS 2025 education allocations include no specific rural consolidation line; funding must come from within the Education Infrastructure Grant (R22.5bn MTEF) by reallocating from new-build to transport and hub-school improvement.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa spends up to four times the national average per learner in its smallest rural schools, while those learners receive fewer subjects and lower-quality instruction than urban peers. — HEDCOM Ministerial Task Team on Rural Education, 2022',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Basic Education / HEDCOM / Provincial MECs',
  feasibility_note = 'Politically sensitive (school closures face community resistance), medium fiscal complexity. Requires provincial cabinet sign-off and coordinated transport procurement. Efficiency gains within existing EIG envelope make this fiscally feasible if phased.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 95;

-- id=123: Just Energy Transition SMME Finance Facility (len=266)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Just Energy Transition Investment Plan (JET-IP, endorsed at COP26, updated 2023) commits R1.5 trillion over 20 years to energy transition, but existing SMME finance instruments—IDC, SEFA, the Small Enterprise Finance Agency—are not configured to serve the specific working-capital and equipment-finance needs of small businesses entering JET sectors: solar panel installation, battery maintenance, building energy audits, EV servicing, and green waste processing. This reform establishes a dedicated JET SMME Finance Facility—a blended-finance vehicle co-capitalised by the Presidency''s JET office, DBSA, the IDC, and international climate finance (GCF, JETP partnership funds)—with standardised loan products of R50,000–R5 million, technical assistance for energy efficiency business-case development, and off-take guarantee instruments to de-risk revenue streams for small installers. The Parliamentary Committee on Small Business Development (November 2022 briefing) identified capital access as the primary barrier preventing SMME participation in JET opportunities, despite the sector''s potential to absorb the 200,000 workers displaced from the coal value chain by 2035. The facility would target 10,000 SMMEs in the first five years, with a R3 billion revolving capital pool.',
  key_quote = 'Without dedicated SMME finance instruments, the Just Energy Transition will be implemented by large corporates and import contractors—missing the job-creation dividend that is the political justification for the programme. — PC on Small Business Development, November 2022',
  responsible_department = 'Presidency JET Office / DBSA / IDC / SEFA / Department of Small Business Development',
  feasibility_note = 'High growth and employment impact. JETP partnership funds (R131bn committed by international partners) provide catalytic capital. Facility design can leverage existing IDC and DBSA origination infrastructure. Fiscally leveraged, not grant-funded.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 123;

-- id=74: SA Satellite Space Programme Commercialisation (len=268)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s space economy strategy, anchored by the South African National Space Agency (SANSA) and the world-class MeerKAT/SKA radio telescope array in the Northern Cape, aims to commercialise earth-observation services, satellite manufacturing, and downstream data analytics. The SA Space Sector Development Framework (2017, updated 2022) targets a R20 billion space economy by 2030. Near-term deliverables include: the launch of the EO-SAT1 earth-observation satellite (under development with Airbus Defence as technology partner, launch planned 2026), commercialisation of SANSA''s space weather monitoring services (which SA provides to the global navigation satellite community), and the positioning of the SKA-adjacent Karoo Science Reserve as a science tourism and spin-off industry anchor. The Parliamentary PC on Science and Technology received updates in April 2025 on the Space Affairs Amendment Act, which updates the SA space licensing regime to attract private satellite operators (including LEO constellation operators) to register in SA. Fiscal context: DSI allocates approximately R180m annually to SANSA; the commercialisation strategy is designed to be self-funding at scale through earth-observation data sales and satellite launch services, with the RF spectrum licensing revenue boosting ICASA receipts.',
  key_quote = 'The SKA and MeerKAT make South Africa the premier radio astronomy location on Earth—building a commercial space economy around this infrastructure is a once-in-a-century opportunity. — DSI Space Affairs Briefing, April 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Science and Innovation / SANSA / ICASA',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility, long-term horizon. EO-SAT1 on track for 2026 launch. Space Affairs Amendment Act updates regulatory framework. Commercialisation path from science infrastructure to industry is long but well-evidenced internationally (ESA model).',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 74;

-- id=98: Expanded Public Works Programme Reform: Towards Skills Pathways (len=268)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Expanded Public Works Programme (EPWP) is South Africa''s largest active employment creation instrument, providing temporary work to approximately 1 million participants annually at a total cost of R15.7 billion (2025/26 MTEF). Despite its scale, EPWP has been consistently criticised in parliamentary BRRRs across the Infrastructure, Public Works, and Employment committees for producing temporary income relief without durable employment: fewer than 5% of EPWP participants transition to permanent employment within 18 months. This reform restructures EPWP exit pathways by: mandating QCTO-aligned training components within EPWP projects (particularly in construction, road maintenance, and environmental management); creating accreditation bridges between EPWP work experience and CETA, CIETA, and MERSETA formal qualifications; and piloting a "P-level to apprenticeship" pathway for EPWP participants in the built environment. The reform connects to the Human Resources Development Council''s (HRDC) artisan pipeline targets (50,000 new artisans by 2030) and the R1 trillion infrastructure programme''s skills demand. Each R1 million of EPWP spending that produces a qualified artisan rather than a temporary work-relief day generates an estimated R120,000 in present-value net lifetime earnings uplift.',
  key_quote = 'EPWP has become a poverty relief programme masquerading as an employment creation strategy. Without skills pathways, we are spending R15 billion a year keeping people temporarily afloat rather than permanently employed. — PC on Public Works BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Public Works and Infrastructure / DPWI / DHET / SETAs',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility, cost-neutral (restructuring within existing R15.7bn EPWP budget). Requires QCTO framework amendments and SETA partnership agreements. Skills pathway reform is administratively complex but builds on existing CETA and CIETA frameworks.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 98;

-- id=110: Tobacco Products and Electronic Delivery Systems Control Act: Passage and Implementation (len=268)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Tobacco Products and Electronic Delivery Systems Control Bill has been before Parliament since 2018, delayed by sustained industry lobbying—the South African tobacco industry spends an estimated R200 million annually on regulatory influence. The Bill would implement WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC) obligations by: banning all tobacco advertising, promotion, and sponsorship; requiring standardised plain packaging; prohibiting smoking in all indoor and outdoor public places; and establishing an evidence-based regulatory framework for e-cigarettes and vaping products that closes the current governance gap allowing unfettered youth marketing. South Africa''s adult tobacco use rate of 21% generates health costs estimated at R42 billion annually (lost productivity, premature mortality, healthcare expenditure). Sin tax revenue from tobacco products contributes approximately R11 billion annually to the fiscus, but this is substantially less than the social costs. The PC on Health BRRRs 2022–2025 consistently flagged the Bill''s passage as a priority. Plain packaging implementation is modelled on Australia''s 2012 legislation, which reduced youth smoking initiation by 3 percentage points within three years.',
  key_quote = 'Every year the Tobacco Bill is delayed, the industry banks the profits and the health system absorbs the costs. South Africa is one of the few FCTC signatories yet to implement plain packaging. — PC on Health BRRR, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Health / Parliament (PC on Health) / SARS',
  feasibility_note = 'High health impact (5/5), fiscally beneficial (reduced healthcare costs outweigh any marginal sin-tax revenue reduction). Bill requires gazetting of final version after parliamentary passage. Industry litigation risk is the primary delay mechanism.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 110;

-- id=73: Advanced Agri-Tech and Food Systems Cluster (len=270)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Advanced Agri-Tech and Food Systems Cluster proposes establishing a CSIR-TIA-led agricultural technology platform focused on three priority areas: drought-resistant crop and livestock adaptation science (critical as the CSIR projects a 15–20% reduction in Western Cape and Karoo rainfall by 2050 under moderate emissions scenarios); precision agriculture technology—soil sensors, satellite imagery, yield-mapping tools—adapted for smallholder scale and African cropping systems; and food-processing technology to capture more value in the fresh produce and protein chains. The ARC (Agricultural Research Council) provides existing research infrastructure in 14 commodity areas; the reform seeks to commercialise ARC outputs more systematically via TIA''s Technology Transfer Office and to build explicit adoption pathways to smallholder farmers via the Agricultural Extension Service (approximately 3,000 extension officers, severely under-resourced). Parliament was briefed on the cluster concept in November 2025 by the PC on Agriculture. Fiscal context: ARC''s parliamentary grant has declined 23% in real terms since 2018; any cluster model must include industry co-funding (through statutory levies collected by commodity organisations—Agri SA, Hortgro, Nerpo—totalling R2.3 billion annually) as a matching requirement.',
  key_quote = 'Climate adaptation in South African agriculture cannot happen through extension officers and pamphlets alone—it requires industrialised research-to-farm pipelines that the ARC and CSIR are uniquely positioned to build. — PC on Agriculture, November 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development / CSIR / ARC / TIA',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. ARC infrastructure exists but is under-resourced. Industry co-funding via commodity levies reduces fiscal cost. Smallholder adoption pathway requires extension officer resourcing. 5-year horizon for commercial-scale outputs.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 73;

-- id=82: Railway Safety Regulator: Independent Enforcement Capacity (len=274)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Railway Safety Regulator (RSR), established under the National Railway Safety Regulator Act (2002), is the statutory body responsible for overseeing the safety of rail operations across PRASA, Transnet Freight Rail, private rail operators, and municipal rail systems. However, the RSR''s operational capacity has not kept pace with the growing complexity of SA''s rail environment: Koeberg nuclear waste rail movements, the expanding private logistics rail network serving renewable energy sites in the Northern Cape, PRASA''s Metrorail recovery programme (R56 billion recapitalisation), and the anticipated new private operators under the open-access rail framework (Transnet reform, id=59). The PC on Transport BRRRs (2022–2024) document chronic RSR understaffing—fewer than 200 inspectors for over 22,000 km of track—and a funding model dependent on operator levies that creates a conflict of interest between regulator and regulated. Reform proposals include: ring-fenced fiscal allocation (R350–500m annually), statutory independence reinforced by Parliamentary Service Authority oversight (analogous to NERSA''s tariff independence), mandatory public incident reporting, and a digital safety management system for real-time track-condition monitoring.',
  key_quote = 'The RSR cannot adequately regulate 22,000 km of rail with 200 inspectors—this is not a regulatory gap, it is a regulatory absence waiting for a catastrophic incident to expose it. — PC on Transport BRRR, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / Railway Safety Regulator / PRASA / Transnet',
  feasibility_note = 'High safety impact, moderate fiscal cost (R350–500m/year). Funding from operator levies can be increased without fiscal appropriation. RSR Act amendment needed to strengthen independence. Aligns with Transnet concessioning reform timeline.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 82;

-- id=100: Government Building Maintenance Budget Ring-fencing (len=275)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s public building portfolio—comprising approximately 95,000 government-owned and leased properties managed by DPWI, provincial DPW departments, and entities—has a replacement value estimated at R700 billion and a maintenance backlog estimated at R97 billion (DPWI Client Asset Register, 2024). Three decades of chronic underfunding of routine maintenance—driven by political incentives that favour new builds over maintenance and by the absence of a mandatory maintenance budget floor—have produced a portfolio where 40% of government buildings are in poor or critical condition. This reform proposes amending the Public Finance Management Act (PFMA) to require all organ of state managing land and building assets to budget a minimum 3% of assessed replacement value annually for planned maintenance, ring-fenced from reprioritisation. The MTBPS 2025 infrastructure envelope of R1 trillion focuses primarily on new builds and SOE capitalisation; without a maintenance mandate, the new assets will follow the same deterioration trajectory. The National Treasury''s Infrastructure Fund, established in 2020, does not cover maintenance. International benchmark: the UK HM Treasury Green Book requires 2–4% annual maintenance provision for public buildings.',
  key_quote = 'The R97 billion building maintenance backlog is the visible accumulation of three decades of deferred costs—each year of further deferral adds R8–12 billion to the eventual bill. — DPWI Client Asset Register, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Public Works and Infrastructure / National Treasury / Provincial DPW Departments',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. PFMA amendment is the vehicle; Treasury will resist any mandatory floor that constrains budget flexibility. Phased implementation (1% in year 1, rising to 3% over five years) reduces the political cost of the mandate.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 100;

-- id=75: Indigenous Knowledge Systems IP and Commercialisation Framework (len=282)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa has approximately 9,600 known medicinal plant species, a global biodiversity hotspot status, and rich indigenous agricultural knowledge documented across San, Khoikhoi, and Bantu-speaking communities. Despite the Nagoya Protocol (ratified by SA in 2013) and the Protection, Promotion, Development and Management of Indigenous Knowledge Systems Act (IKS Act, signed 2024 after 15 years of drafting), the legal and institutional machinery for protecting indigenous knowledge (IK) and enabling benefit-sharing with origin communities remains largely non-operational. This reform operationalises the IKS Act by: establishing the National Indigenous Knowledge Systems Office (NIKSO) database of documented IK assets; implementing the benefit-sharing agreement registry required by the Biodiversity Act amendments; creating fast-track IP protection for IK-derived products under the Patents Act (currently IK cannot be patented but it cannot be adequately defended against biopiracy either); and launching 10 pilot commercialisation partnerships between IK communities, CSIR, and private sector buyers in the cosmetics, nutraceuticals, and pharmaceutical sectors. The rooibos benefit-sharing agreement (2019) with San and Khoikhoi communities—which secured an estimated R12 million in annual royalties—is the template.',
  key_quote = 'The rooibos agreement demonstrates that equitable benefit-sharing of indigenous knowledge is achievable—what is needed now is the institutional infrastructure to replicate this across thousands of products. — Department of Science and Innovation, IKS Policy Framework, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Science and Innovation / NIKSO / DTIC / DALRRD',
  feasibility_note = 'IKS Act signed 2024—implementation regulations are the immediate deliverable. NIKSO establishment requires R80–120m annual budget. Pilot commercialisation partnerships can be self-funded through industry participation. Benefit-sharing model well-evidenced.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 75;

-- id=93: Learner Transport Policy: Funded National Programme (len=286)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Approximately 700,000 South African learners walk more than 5 km to school daily, with rural learners in Limpopo, Eastern Cape, and KwaZulu-Natal averaging 8–12 km. The DBE''s 2022 learner transport audit documents a direct link between transport burden, attendance rates (absent 2+ days/month vs. 0.3 days for transported learners), and dropout rates. Despite this evidence, South Africa has no nationally funded learner transport programme: the function falls to provincial education departments, which receive no dedicated conditional grant for it, resulting in highly unequal provincial provision (Western Cape transports 48,000 learners; Eastern Cape less than 10,000 despite a larger rural school population). This reform proposes establishing a Learner Transport Conditional Grant (estimated R6–8 billion annually at full implementation) administered through the Division of Revenue Act, with: minimum service standards (maximum walk distance 3 km); integration with rural school consolidation (id=95) planning; procurement through provincial transport authorities using standardised contracts; and GPS tracking linked to attendance reporting systems. The PC on Basic Education''s BRRR 2024 recommends the conditional grant as the immediate instrument, noting that current inequity in learner transport is directly related to the urban-rural learning outcomes gap.',
  key_quote = 'A child walking 10 km to school is not in a position to learn—learner transport is not a luxury, it is a prerequisite for education delivery in rural South Africa. — PC on Basic Education BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Basic Education / Department of Transport / Provincial Education Departments',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate cost (R6–8bn/year at full rollout). Phased implementation through conditional grant is feasible. Rural school consolidation (id=95) reduces per-learner transport cost by concentrating demand. DoT and DBE coordination is the institutional challenge.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 93;

-- id=48: National Nuclear Regulator: Capacity for New Build Oversight (len=290)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Nuclear Regulator (NNR), established under the NNR Act (1999), oversees nuclear safety across Koeberg Nuclear Power Station (1,860 MW, undergoing long-term operation extension to 2044), the SAFARI-1 research reactor at Necsa, nuclear medicine facilities, and radiation sources in industry and medicine. The government''s nuclear new build programme—targeting 2,500 MW from new nuclear sites under the Integrated Resource Plan 2019 update (IRP 2019)—creates an entirely new regulatory burden: site licensing, design approval, construction oversight, and operator qualification for technologies (likely KPWER small modular reactors from South Korea or AP1000 from Westinghouse) that the NNR has not previously reviewed. The National Nuclear Regulator Amendment Bill (tabled 2023) updates the NNR''s inspection powers, emergency preparedness requirements, environmental impact oversight responsibilities, and fee structures. Parliamentary PC on Minerals and Energy BRRRs (2022–2024) have consistently flagged NNR''s technical staff shortage (fewer than 120 licensed nuclear safety professionals vs. the 400 estimated as necessary for oversight of a new build programme) and salary competitiveness gaps relative to the nuclear energy sector. Fiscal estimate: NNR budget must grow from R380m to R750m annually to match the new mandate.',
  key_quote = 'You cannot build new nuclear capacity with a regulator that cannot attract or retain the engineers needed to review the designs—NNR strengthening must precede any new build procurement process. — PC on Minerals and Energy BRRR, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / National Nuclear Regulator / Necsa',
  feasibility_note = 'High regulatory necessity. NNR Amendment Bill provides legal basis. Budget doubling (R380m to R750m) is achievable through industry levy increases. Staff recruitment in a globally competitive nuclear labour market is the binding constraint.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 48;

-- id=92: Mother-Tongue Based Multilingual Education Scale-up (len=292)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The 2021 PIRLS results—which placed 81% of SA Grade 4 learners below minimum reading proficiency—provide the most powerful evidence base for language-in-education reform: children taught in a language they do not understand at home cannot build foundational literacy. South Africa''s Language in Education Policy (LiEP, 1997) supports mother-tongue instruction through Grade 3, but implementation is highly uneven, with most isiZulu, isiXhosa, Sesotho, and Setswana-speaking learners transitioning to English instruction in Grade 2 under parental pressure and school convenience. This reform proposes legislating mother-tongue based multilingual education (MTB-MLE) as the mandatory foundation phase approach through Grade 3, with a structured transition to English from Grade 4, supported by: a national graded reader programme in all 11 official languages (estimated R1.2 billion for library stock); teacher training in structured literacy pedagogy in African languages (DHET-coordinated, using Wits School of Education''s evidence-based phonics programme as the template); and a classroom assessment system that measures mother-tongue literacy, not just English. The BELA Act (id=86) provides legislative cover for mother-tongue enforcement. Ethiopia, Tanzania, and Rwanda''s MTB-MLE programmes provide African comparators showing 0.5–0.9 standard-deviation gains in Grade 6 literacy when foundational language instruction is implemented consistently.',
  key_quote = '81% of South African Grade 4 learners cannot read for meaning—this disaster is constructed in part by a language policy that teaches children in a language they do not yet understand. — PIRLS 2021 South Africa Country Report',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Basic Education / DHET / Pan South African Language Board',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact (5/5). Main cost is teacher training and graded reader production (R1.2–2bn over 5 years). BELA Act provides enforcement mechanism. PanSALB and the DHET language units provide institutional base. Parental choice pressures require sustained community communication campaigns.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 92;

-- id=103: Urban Land Release for Affordable Housing and Infrastructure (len=293)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s housing backlog exceeds 2.4 million formal dwelling units, predominantly in urban metros where well-located state-owned land sits idle while poor households are pushed to urban peripheries. Government at all levels—national, provincial, and municipal—holds vast tracts of under-utilised urban land: disused SANDF bases, vacant DPWI parcels, underperforming SOE-owned land (Transnet rail yards adjacent to city centres), and Housing Development Agency (HDA) acquisitions that have not been developed. The HDA was established in 2008 specifically to identify, acquire, and release state land for housing; nearly two decades later, its release pipeline remains glacial due to intergovernmental coordination failures and SOE land-holding rigidities. This reform operationalises the Presidential Urban Land Release Mechanism (announced 2023, under-implemented): establishing a statutory urban land register of under-utilised state land in the eight metros; setting mandatory disposal timelines (2-year maximum from identification to tender) enforced by the National Treasury conditional grant framework; enabling municipalities to impose holding costs on non-compliant national departments; and fast-tracking Environmental Impact Assessment processes for social housing on pre-identified land. The Urban Development Zone (UDZ) tax incentive should be extended and reformed to channel private capital into social housing on released land.',
  key_quote = 'The state is simultaneously the largest urban landowner and the entity most paralysed by its own bureaucratic complexity—South Africa debates land expropriation while leaving state land idle. — Housing Development Agency Annual Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'DPWI / HDA / Transnet / Municipal Governments / Department of Human Settlements',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, complex coordination. Urban land register creation is achievable within 18 months. Mandatory disposal timelines require PFMA amendment or NT directive. SOE land release (Transnet) requires political commitment at Cabinet level. UDZ reform is low-cost, high-leverage.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 103;

-- id=119: SEDA Digital Transformation and Specialist Sector Hubs (len=293)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Small Enterprise Development Agency (SEDA) operates 54 branch offices nationally, providing advisory services to approximately 140,000 SMMEs annually—but reach-per-rand analysis in DSBD evaluation studies shows low impact rates: fewer than 15% of SEDA clients report measurable business improvement within 18 months. The core problem is SEDA''s walk-in generalist model, which cannot serve digitally active urban SMMEs or deliver specialised advice in high-potential sectors. This reform proposes a hybrid digital-physical transformation: launching a SEDA Digital Portal with quality-assured business diagnostic tools, curated mentor matching (using the Sukuma Relief Programme''s NGO mentor network as a template), and sector-specific online learning modules; establishing 12 specialist sector hubs co-located with incubators in agri-processing (Limpopo), tourism (Mpumalanga, KZN), ICT/fintech (Cape Town, Johannesburg), and manufacturing (Tshwane, eThekwini); and replacing generalist advisors with sector-specialist mentors drawn from the private sector under a National Mentorship Programme (analogous to Malaysia''s SME Corp specialist programme). The MTBPS 2025 allocates R1.4 billion to the DSBD vote; SEDA receives approximately R550m. The digital transformation is estimated to cost R200m in additional capex, reaching 500,000 SMMEs annually by year 5 at significantly lower cost per touch.',
  key_quote = 'SEDA''s walk-in model reaches 140,000 SMMEs with a 15% impact rate—we need a digital-first platform that can reach 500,000 SMMEs with a 40% impact rate at lower cost per client. — DSBD SEDA Evaluation Report, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Small Business Development / SEDA / DSBD',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility, moderate upfront cost (R200m digital platform). Existing SEDA branch network provides physical anchor. DSBD 2025 BRRR recommends digital transformation. Mentor network can be built through NSBC and private sector partnerships. 5-year transformation horizon.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 119;

-- id=102: Green Building Standards Mandate for Government Properties (len=295)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The national government estate consumes approximately R8.3 billion in electricity annually across state-owned and leased buildings, making it one of the country''s largest electricity customers and a significant driver of Eskom load during peak periods. Despite the Energy Efficiency and Demand-Side Management programme (EEDSM), established under the National Energy Act and administered by DoE, most government buildings have undergone no material energy efficiency retrofit since construction. This reform proposes a mandatory Green Building Standard for all new government buildings and major refurbishments (above R10 million in project value): minimum 4-star Green Star SA rating (equivalent to 40% below baseline energy consumption); mandatory solar PV installation on all buildings with suitable roofline; solar hot water heaters replacing electric geysers in all public facilities; and water conservation measures (rainwater harvesting, flow restrictors) meeting SANS 10400 XA standards. The Department of Public Works manages the Government Immovable Asset Management Act (GIAMA) framework, which already requires lifecycle costing—the reform extends GIAMA to include mandatory energy performance certificates. Fiscal case: a 30% reduction in the government electricity bill saves R2.5 billion annually, with a capital payback period of 4–6 years at current solar costs. The MTBPS 2025 green infrastructure allocation of R4.2 billion provides partial capital cover.',
  key_quote = 'Government spends R8.3 billion on electricity annually in buildings that were often never designed for energy efficiency—retrofitting this estate is both a climate commitment and a R2.5 billion annual saving. — DPWI Energy Efficiency Audit, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Public Works and Infrastructure / DoE / National Treasury',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility, positive NPV. GIAMA provides regulatory vehicle; amendment is modest. Green Star SA rating system is established. Solar costs have fallen to R11–14/Watt installed—payback under 5 years. Capital can be structured as energy performance contracts with private sector.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 102;

-- id=114: National Small Enterprise Amendment Act: Ombud Service Operationalisation (impact 4)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Small Enterprise Amendment Act (2024) established the Small Enterprise Ombud Service (SEOS), a quasi-judicial body empowered to adjudicate commercial disputes between SMMEs and large corporations or government entities without requiring litigation. The Ombud''s jurisdiction covers: payment disputes (government''s failure to pay SMMEs within the 30-day mandate is the largest category), contract cancellations, regulatory non-compliance by large entities, and unfair procurement practices. Determinations are binding and enforceable through the normal courts without re-litigation. The 30-day payment rule — in force since National Treasury Instruction Note 34 (2020) — is honoured in fewer than 50% of government transactions with SMMEs according to DSBD''s 2024 monitoring survey, costing small businesses R18 billion annually in working capital tied up in overdue government invoices. Operationalisation requires: appointment of the Chief Ombud and 3 Deputies, 12 regional offices (1 per province plus Gauteng East/West split), 200+ adjudicators and administrators, a digital case management system, and a public awareness campaign. The PC on Small Business Development BRRR 2024 identifies the Ombud as the highest-priority DSBD implementation deliverable for 2025. SEOS''s first year performance target is to clear 80% of cases within 90 days.',
  key_quote = 'Government owes SMMEs R18 billion in overdue payments — the 30-day rule is honoured in the breach, costing small businesses the working capital that could fund their growth. The Ombud is the enforcement mechanism that makes the rule real. — DSBD Payment Survey, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Small Business Development / Small Enterprise Ombud Service',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win. Legislative basis established. Ombud appointment and budget allocation (R280 million in 2025/26) are immediate deliverables. Digital case management system is the infrastructure priority. Enforcement of determinations through courts provides credibility.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 114;
